    "narrative": "For April 20, the Ghost Ride the WHIP lineup is anchored by **Austin Riley** (71.53) and **James Wood** (69.33), our clear top-tier options. **Austin Riley** benefits from a high-upside matchup against the right-handed Irvin, where a favorable park factor and strong platoon edge against a mid-tier xERA pitcher propel him into the elite scoring bracket. **James Wood** remains a priority start, leveraging the premium lead-off spot against Elder to maximize his counting stat opportunities. Additionally, **Tyler Soderstrom** offers strong value (65.09) in our anticipated lineup; despite the park penalty, the platoon advantage against Hancock keeps his efficiency well above the threshold, making him a high-floor play for those chasing HRs and RBI.\n\nThe middle of the order presents a tighter squeeze, particularly at the UTIL spot where **Vinnie Pasquantino** (55.86) gets the nod despite a daunting matchup against the elite arm of Bradish (2.63 xERA). We are banking on his dynamic platoon advantage and a wind-aided park boost to bridge the gap against a difficult pitcher. Regarding our bench, **Kyle Karros** (44.18) was the closest contender for a starting spot; while his platoon advantage against a left-handed pitcher is clear, his lower spot in the batting order and the general scarcity of elite production from the bench meant he could not unseat our projected starters. We remain cautious regarding **Max Muncy** and **Tyler Soderstrom**, as their status remains \"Lineup Pending.\" Should the official lineups shift these two down the order or out of the lineup entirely, we will re-evaluate the utility of **Zach McKinstry** or **Alex Freeland** to protect our game caps. Investors should also note the total absence of stolen base threats like **Corbin Carroll**, **Jose Caballero**, and **Brice Turang** from today\u2019s active slate due to team off-days, which places the burden of production squarely on our power-hitting core.",
